The issue you are facing is due to the fact that you are using the `read()` method of the `FileInputStream` to read the entire contents of the encrypted file into memory as a byte array before decrypting it. This approach is not recommended as it can lead to memory issues, especially if the encrypted file is large.

Instead, you should use the `InputStream.read()` method to read the encrypted file in small chunks, decrypt each chunk, and then write the decrypted data back to the output file. This approach will ensure that you can handle large files without running out of memory.

Here's an updated version of your decryption function that reads the encrypted file in small chunks and decrypts each chunk before writing it to the output file:
```java
public static void decrypt(byte[] key, File inputFile, File outputFile) throws Exception {
    try {
        Key secretKey = new SecretKeySpec(key, "AES");
        Cipher cipher = Cipher.getInstance("AES");
        cipher.init(Cipher.DECRYPT_MODE, secretKey);

        FileInputStream inputStream = new FileInputStream(inputFile);
        byte[] buffer = new byte[1024]; // adjust this buffer size according to your needs
        int bytesRead;
        while ((bytesRead = inputStream.read(buffer)) != -1) {
            byte[] decryptedBuffer = cipher.doFinal(buffer, 0, bytesRead);
            FileOutputStream outputStream = new FileOutputStream(outputFile, true);
            outputStream.write(decryptedBuffer);
            outputStream.close();
        }
        inputStream.close();
    } catch (Exception ex) {
        ex.printStackTrace();
    }
}
```
With this updated decryption function, you should no longer see extra trash characters in the decrypted log file.
